The display is located in the Dunagan Library foyer.

Don‚Äôt forget to visit the ‚ÄúSuffrage Movement‚Äù display case presented by the History Department. To view the ‚ÄúSuffrage Movement‚Äù display visit the lobby of the Mesa Building (southside as you enter the front of the building).

post_text:
UT Permian Basin alum, Bill Decker recently decided to donate his lifelong mineral collection to the University.

‚ÄúI have enjoyed collecting minerals and looking at the collection. As we get older, there comes a time when you should let others enjoy it. After putting such an effort into accumulating the collection, I didn't want it to be discarded or put somewhere it would be forgotten.‚Äù

Decker graduated from UTPB in 1983 with a Bachelor‚Äôs degree in Criminal Justice. Faculty and students studying geology and geosciences will learn from and study Decker‚Äôs collection for years to come.

‚ÄúI am grateful that the collection has a home and will be used to help educate students. I hope it creates an interest in mineralogy, chemistry, math, and awareness of natural resources and their economical and industrial uses.‚Äù

The collection will be on display in the new Geosciences Building.

Learn more about the donation:
https://www.utpb.edu/community-impact/impact-stories/2020/09/mineral-collection-donated

post_text:
UTPB Alum, Kelby Davis reflected back on her time spent at UT Permian Basin and shared her personal story of how the August 31 mass shooting affected her family. Her husband, Garret, is also a UTPB alum.

"Our daughter Anderson (17 months old at the time) was shot the day of the shooting while we sat in our car at a red light right next to the UTPB campus. The events of that day were tragic, but it is the aftermath of the event that I hope people remember and want to share with you today. My time at UTPB taught me how important it is to be a community of people working together to support each other in all aspects of our lives."

To read her full blog post, click the link below:
https://www.utpb.edu/news/2020/09/alumni-blog-kelby-davis

Kirk Edwards Family Human Performance Center, student housing, the SAC, and admissions. Chancellor Milliken said providing a high quality education, even during the pandemic, remains top priority.

‚ÄúWe will continue to offer high quality education to those who depend on it and expect it,‚Äù said Chancellor Milliken. ‚ÄúWe learned that our students want to be together to learn so we are creating environments here at UTPB and across the UT System where we can do that in the safest way possible.‚Äù

Come back and see us soon, Chancellor! #FalconsUp

The Lone Star Conference Council of Presidents voted Friday to postpone the start of the football, soccer, and volleyball seasons to the spring due to concerns surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic. Lower-risk sports of cross country, golf, and tennis will be allowed to compete in the fall starting September 21. They also voted to push the start of competition of basketball back to the spring, but may practice starting October 15.

‚ÄúStudent-athlete welfare is our number one priority as a department,‚Äù said Director of Athletics Scott Farmer. ‚ÄúThe conference could not proceed without a safe path to maintain the health of our student-athletes and put them at unnecessary risk.‚Äù

Click the link below for more information and follow UTPB Athletics.

https://utpbfalcons.com/news/2020/8/7/general-lone-star-conference-postpones-team-sports-until-the-spring.aspx

The Division II Presidents Council made the decision Wednesday to cancel fall championships for the 2020-21 academic year due to the operational, logistical and financial challenges caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.

The council made the move after the NCAA Board of Governors gave each division an August 21 deadline to decide on the fate of fall championships. The Board of Governors also gave additional directions on student-athlete safety and a 50% sponsorship threshold to hold fall championships. At the time of the decision, 11 of the 23 Division II conferences had postponed their fall seasons.

The Lone Star Conference Council of Presidents meets on Friday to discuss this issue. The UT Permian Basin Athletics Department will have no further comment until receiving direction from the Conference Presidents.

For more follow UTPB Athletics or visit www.utpbfalcons.com

https://utpbfalcons.com/news/2020/8/5/presidents-cancel-fall-2020.aspx

Calling all Future Falcons: It's time for you to SOAR!
That means "Student Orientation And Registration."

- All admitted freshmen and transfer students need to register for and complete orientation (SOAR). You can do that by accessing your student account. Call (432) 552-2651 if you have questions!

- Freshmen will be contacted by the Academic Advising office to finalize their schedules once SOAR is complete .

- Transfer students can email Academic Advising before or after SOAR to get signed up for classes. Just contact advising@utpb.edu

Questions? Email orientation@utpb.edu.

We are thrilled to share this update on international students:

Today, federal officials agreed to rescind the July 6, 2020 Policy Directive and the July 7, 2020 FAQ relating to international students. With the new directive rescinded, schools will follow previous ICE guidance from March that allows flexibility regarding student visa eligibility. More information from International Student Support Services is forthcoming.

This is great news for all international students! UT Permian Basin values what our international students bring to our campus and community and look forward to the fall semester ahead.

Do you have a child getting ready to enter kindergarten? It‚Äôs a big step for both the student and their families, so now is the time to make sure they are ready for the classroom!

For years, First 5 Permian Basin has helped prepare West Texas families for the transition through an in-person Kinder Camp. First 5 is excited to announce Kinder Camp will still happen this summer, it will just look a little different due to COVID-19.

To keep families healthy, Kinder Camp will be offered virtually this year. Karla Juarez, First 5 Permian Basin‚Äôs Community Engagement and Data Coordinator, said Kinder Camp is about more than just getting future students ready. It‚Äôs also about preparing parents.

‚ÄúThough camp traditionally focuses on the children‚Äôs transition, we are utilizing this virtual experience to place focus on the family engagement aspect and include skills for parents to utilize once their children enter school.‚Äù

Click the link below to learn more and to register for the FREE camp today!

https://www.utpb.edu/community-impact/impact-stories/2020/06/kinder-camp-online

UT Permian Basin remains committed to stand against racism, violence, hatred, and bigotry. We hold firm to our mission to be a place where diversity is celebrated and racism is not tolerated. No test scores? No problem.

In light of COVID-19 UTPB is waiving SAT/ACT test scores for summer AND Fall 2020 admission for FIRST TIME FRESHMEN. We'll accept self-reported GPAs and class ranks plus no transcripts are required to be accepted!

Please note: The GRE and GMAT will be waived for specific graduate programs. Please email gradstudies@utpb.edu for more information. Transfer students will be accepted with unofficial transcripts from their college or university attended.

post_text:
UT Permian Basin continues to take steps to protect our community from the spread of COVID-19.

The College of Engineering teamed up with West Texas 3D COVID 19 Relief Consortium to design and create a stand alone, clear, plexi-glass, booth. The booth will allow medical personnel to test patients for COVID19 without wearing any additional personal protection equipment (PPE) besides medical grade heavy-duty nitrile gloves. The testing booth was delivered to Odessa Regional Medical Center on Thursday.

Watch below to learn more about the testing booth and how it will help preserve PPE in West Texas.

University of Texas System

While store shelves are void of toilet paper, paper towels, and the hottest commodity: hand sanitizer, UT Permian Basin‚Äôs chemistry department is mixing up their own solution.

‚ÄúOne of the biggest troubles we saw in the community was that first responders were running low on hand sanitizer, so we immediately began researching the materials we would need. I discussed the idea with one of my students, Mikayla Rodriguez, and she eagerly joined the effort,‚Äù said Chemistry Department Chair, Dr. Milka Montes.

Click below to read more on how Dr. Montes and Mikayla researched and created "Falcon hand sanitizer" for our first responders!

https://www.utpb.edu/community-impact/impact-stories/2020/04/falcon-hand-sanitizer

Hey Falcons!

After the town hall meeting with Dr. Spurlock earlier this week, we noticed some students asking for an extension for the RA application. We want to make sure that everyone who is interested has an opportunity to apply! To be considered for a position for the Fall 2020 semester, you need to submit an application by 12pm, Monday April 20th. Recommendation letters are optional but not required for submission.

If you have any questions, concerns, or just want to chat about the RA position, please reach out to us by emailing housing@utpb.edu to schedule a virtual meeting or call.

Check your UTPB email for a link to apply!

The University of Texas Permian Basin is working closely with Medical Center Health System and Odessa Regional Medical Center to provide housing during the COVID-19 response for those who need it most: our local medical heroes. During this crisis it remains a top priority for UT Permian Basin to help the West Texas community and giveback to those who are serving others.

It‚Äôs important to note that no students are currently in these buildings.The buildings and parking lots are separate from the limited number of students who remain in emergency housing. Each apartment has its own air conditioning unit and includes a kitchen - making the spaces ideal while following CDC guidelines and social distancing.

Click the link below to learn more about this new partnership:

https://www.utpb.edu/community-impact/impact-stories/2020/04/housing-for-medical-heroes

UTPB College of Nursing has teamed up with Ector County to try to stop the spread of COVID-19 in our community.

Today, 22 nursing students began training with the Ector
County Health Department. Students will soon be calling people who might have come in contact with someone who tested positive for the Coronavirus, tracking the illness, and guiding them on the next steps to take. Way to make us proud, Falcons!

Read more about this project by clicking the link below:

https://www.utpb.edu/community-impact/impact-stories/2020/04/nursing-students-help-fight-covid-19

#FalconsUp #WeAreFalconNursing #UTPB

post_text:
UTPB ENGINEERS DESIGN LIFE-SAVING MEDICAL EQUIPMENT FOR COVID-19 RESPONSE:

The University of Texas Permian Basin is part of a collaborative effort to help those who are on the front lines of the COVID-19 pandemic: our healthcare workers.

UTPB Engineers along with Texas Tech University Health Science Center faculty have designed prototypes for two important medical devices: face shields and splitters used for ventilators. Then, they brought in several community partners to utilize 3D printers from around West Texas and even pilots to make deliveries.

Read more here:

https://www.utpb.edu/community-impact/impact-stories/2020/04/utpb-designs-life-saving-equipment

University of Texas System

TUESDAY, MARCH 24 COVID-19 UPDATE:

The University is now closed to public access. Walking trails are open to the public if adhering to CDC guidance on social distancing.

Beginning Friday, March 27th, most employees will be telecommuting for most of their hours. If you are required to be on campus your supervisor will let you know, otherwise complete all your work remotely.

All working meetings necessary to continue operations should continue uninterrupted and can be managed through Microsoft Teams.

Employees, please make sure you‚Äôve signed the UTPB Telecommuting Agreement. If you have not received it, ask your supervisor.

For more information please visit: https://www.utpb.edu/coronavirus

UTPB COVID-19 UPDATE:

This afternoon The University of Texas Permian Basin was made aware that one of our employees who works at the Small Business Development Center (SBDC) at the CEED Building tested positive for COVID-19. The employee has confirmed he is from Crane.

UT Permian Basin can also confirm that the employee has not been at work since March 13 and to our knowledge he was only on the CEED campus ‚Äì not on any of the other University campuses. There are less than 10 employees who work in the CEED building. State health officials are contacting people who need to take precautionary steps.

Starting tomorrow (Friday, March 20) all UTPB employees will begin telecommuting. The University will still be serving students, faculty, staff, and the community.

AVID students from every high school in Odessa spent part of their day at UT Permian Basin today.

Hosted by Complex Community FCU, the group of seniors explored how past challenges impact their outlook on the future. Then they used a beautiful art project to symbolize the hope and excitement that awaits them in the future. To end the day we all celebrated with a big lunch at the UTPB dining hall. Thanks to Complex Community FCU for letting us play a role in this important day! We hope they will all be #FutureFalcons!

There‚Äôs no better way to celebrate Valentine's Day eve than with another UT Permian Basin love story (we're swooning!)

"I met the love my life here at UTPB! We had the same physics class our 2nd year here. I sat in the front of the class while Trey sat in the back. Every class he would move down a row just so he could get close to me until finally we were on the same row. Then he started offering to walk me back to my dorm. If it wasn‚Äôt for UTPB we would have never met. Now we are both on our last year of petroleum engineering and we have been dating for 2 years." -Estefany Olivarez UTPB Alumni

text: UTPB Winter Weather AlertDue to deteriorating weather conditions, all classes tonight (2/4) are canceled for UTPB. On Wednesday (2/5) the University will be closed all day. The closure includes the UTPB STEM Academy. The University encourages you to stay off the roads and be safe.

post_text:
ATTENTION FALCONS:

Due to increasing bad weather and hazardous road conditions, The University of Texas Permian Basin is canceling evening classes for Tuesday, February 4.

UT Permian Basin and UTPB STEM Academy will also be closed all day on Wednesday, February 5. The University encourages students, faculty, and staff to stay home and safe. The US National Weather Service has issued a winter storm warning for the region.

On-campus dining will be available to students from 8:30 am- 8pm on Wednesday only in the residence dining hall.

Please note, the Champions Fund Signing Day Breakfast which was scheduled for 7 a.m. on Wednesday, February 5 has been cancelled.

The University will re-open to regular hours on Thursday, February 6.

UT Permian Basin plans to help students, faculty, and staff learn about trauma and it‚Äôs effect on our health through workshops, presentations and trainings.
